<main class="zen-page" id="top">
    <section class="zen-intro" id="journey">
        <p class="zen-kicker">Peaceful Filmmaker Journal</p>
        <h1 class="zen-title">A Single Quiet Page For Roads, Cinema, And People</h1>
        <p>This page is an open notebook. It does not rush, it does not shout, and it does not decorate pain. It simply stays present with the journey: train windows, long bus rides, rehearsal rooms, and the difficult tenderness of independent filmmaking in India.</p>
        <p>Some entries begin with landscapes, some with protests, some with a single face in afternoon light. Every note here is written with care, because people are not content blocks. They are the reason the camera is lifted in the first place.</p>
        <p class="zen-hashtags">#peacefulfilmmaker #roadcinema #indiadiary #visualjournal</p>
    </section>

    <section class="zen-topic" id="cinema">
        <h2>Cinema Practice</h2>
        <p>Filmmaking here is not a clean pipeline. It is often a borrowed room, uncertain funding, and stories that keep changing as life keeps speaking. The process is imperfect, but this imperfection is also where truth enters. Cuts become sharper when lived experience is allowed to breathe.</p>
        <p>Scripts are drafted between movement and waiting. One scene comes from a station platform, another from an unfinished conversation, another from silence after a crowd disperses. Craft grows slowly, through listening and returning to the same question: what deserves to be seen with dignity.</p>
        <p class="zen-hashtags">#independentcinema #directorsnotebook #craftandcompassion #slowcinema</p>
    </section>

    <section class="zen-topic" id="travel">
        <h2>Travel Notes Across India</h2>
        <p>Travel is not treated as tourism here. It is study. It is relational. It is the labor of staying awake to place, language, food, weather, and memory. Distances teach rhythm, and rhythm teaches editing. Roads are not background; roads are narrative structure.</p>
        <p>From small tea stalls to crowded city crossings, every location holds a distinct social texture. The notebook keeps these textures alive so the films remain rooted. The goal is not exotic imagery. The goal is attention.</p>
        <p class="zen-hashtags">#traveljournal #fieldnotes #indiaonfoot #livedgeography</p>
    </section>

    <section class="zen-topic" id="people-politics">
        <h2>People And Politics</h2>
        <p>Political voice in this space comes from lived realities, not from performance. The writing carries the concerns of marginalized communities, laboring bodies, and unheard speech. Cinema is treated as witness: a way to hold complexity without flattening people into symbols.</p>
        <p>These notes are built with restraint and responsibility. Anger appears where needed, but it is grounded in care. The long view matters. Change is not a single headline; it is a sequence of small acts, repeated with conviction.</p>
        <p class="zen-hashtags">#socialjustice #casteequity #cinemaaswitness #publicvoice</p>
    </section>

    <section class="zen-topic" id="photo-essays">
        <h2>Photo Essays</h2>
        <p>Photographs here function as fragments of a larger film. A hand on a ticket counter, dust in backlight, people waiting without complaint, rain over old concrete. The image language stays minimal so that presence leads and styling follows.</p>
        <p>Each essay invites slow looking. The frame is not an object to consume quickly; it is a place to stand for a moment. That pause is part of the ethic of this page.</p>
        <p class="zen-hashtags">#photoessay #monochromemood #streetportrait #cinematicstillness</p>
    </section>

    <section class="zen-topic" id="contact">
        <h2>Collaborate</h2>
        <p>If you are a producer, editor, cinematographer, activist, writer, or curator who values human-centered storytelling, this project is open to collaboration. The intent is to build films and essays that stay close to people while remaining formally thoughtful.</p>
        <p>Use this page as an entry point. Read, watch, and reach out with context. Slow meaningful collaboration is preferred over rapid noisy output.</p>
        <p class="zen-hashtags">#collaboration #indiefilmnetwork #storyfirst #humanecinema</p>
        <p><a href="#top">Back to top</a></p>
    </section>

    <section class="zen-topic" id="latest-posts">
        <h2>Latest Journal Entries</h2>
        <p>These entries come directly from the live publication stream. The intention is to keep this homepage as a calm single page while still making every recent story easy to open and read in full.</p>
        {{#get "posts" filter="type:post+status:published" limit="12" as |entries|}}
            <div class="zen-post-list">
                {{#foreach entries}}
                    <article class="zen-post-item" aria-label="Post: {{title}}">
                        {{#if feature_image}}
                            <a class="zen-post-image-wrap" href="{{url}}" aria-label="{{title}}">
                                <img class="zen-post-image" src="{{img_url feature_image size="l"}}" alt="{{title}}">
                            </a>
                        {{/if}}

                        <h3><a href="{{url}}">{{title}}</a></h3>

                        <div class="zen-post-meta" aria-hidden="false">
                            {{#if primary_author}}<span class="meta-author">{{primary_author.name}}</span>{{/if}}
                            <span class="meta-sep"> &middot; </span>
                            <time datetime="{{published_at}}">{{date published_at format="MMMM D, YYYY"}}</time>
                            <span class="meta-sep"> &middot; </span>
                            <span class="meta-reading">{{reading_time}} min read</span>
                        </div>

                        {{#if custom_excerpt}}
                            <p>{{custom_excerpt}}</p>
                        {{else}}
                            <p>{{plaintext words="32"}}</p>
                        {{/if}}

                        <p class="zen-hashtags">
                            {{#foreach tags limit="3"}}
                                <a href="{{url}}" aria-label="Tag: {{name}}">#{{name}}</a>
                            {{/foreach}}
                        </p>
                    </article>
                {{/foreach}}
            </div>
        {{/get}}
    </section>
</main>
